<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,310,1724,1750]" box="[189,310,1724,1750]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1724,1750]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1724,1750]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1399,1773,1874]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName box="[189,497,1773,1799]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="karangputihensis">
<emphasis box="[189,497,1773,1799]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Begonia karangputihensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the peltate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="N. E. Br. (Brown" authorityYear="1882" box="[787,951,1774,1799]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="goegoensis">
<emphasis box="[787,951,1774,1799]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">B. goegoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is also native to 
<collectingRegion box="[1234,1399,1773,1800]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Barat" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">West Sumatra</collectingRegion>
in being a smaller plant, with smaller (up to 
<quantity box="[709,767,1811,1837]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="cm" value="7.0">7 cm</quantity>
wide, not 
<emphasis box="[890,910,1811,1836]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">c.</emphasis>
<quantity box="[918,1020,1810,1837]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="cm" value="12.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="9.0">9–15 cm</quantity>
wide), less rugose leaves, terete petioles (not triangular) and flowers with flat membranous tepals (not cup-shaped and fleshy).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,324,1915,1941]" box="[189,324,1915,1941]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1915,1941]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1915,1941]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1398,1963,2027]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
The epithet is derived from Bukit Karang Putih, an area of limestone within Lubuk Kilangan district, 
<collectingRegion box="[189,355,2001,2027]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Barat" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">West Sumatra</collectingRegion>
, near the Semen Padang mine. In English the name of the area means “white coral hill”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
